### Current Inventory and Capabilities

The RSAF's inventory reflects its commitment to maintaining a technologically advanced air force. Its combat aircraft include a substantial fleet of [Eurofighter Typhoons](/Eurofighter_Typhoon), [Panavia Tornados](/Panavia_Tornado), and various models of the [F-15 Eagle](/McDonnell_Douglas_F-15_Eagle) series, including the [F-15SA](/Boeing_F-15EX_Eagle_II) variant. For airborne early warning and control, it operates [Boeing E-3 Sentry](/Boeing_E-3_Sentry) and [Saab 2000 AEW&C](/Saab_2000) aircraft.

Aerial refueling capabilities are provided by [Boeing KC-707](/Boeing_707) (KE-3A), [KC-130 Hercules](/Lockheed_Martin_KC-130) variants, and the modern [Airbus A330 MRTT](/Airbus_A330_MRTT) (KC-30A). The transport fleet relies heavily on the [C-130 Hercules](/Lockheed_C-130_Hercules) family, complemented by various light transports and VIP aircraft. The helicopter inventory includes [Bell 212](/Bell_UH-1N_Twin_Huey), [Bell 412](/Bell_412), [Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk](/Sikorsky_UH-60_Black_Hawk), and [Eurocopter AS332 Cougar](/Eurocopter_AS332_Cougar) models.

Pilot training is conducted on advanced platforms such as the [BAE Hawk](/BAE_Systems_Hawk), [Pilatus PC-21](/Pilatus_PC-21), [Cirrus SR22](/Cirrus_SR22), and [PAC MFI-17 Mushshak](/PAC_MFI-17_Mushshak). The RSAF also operates a considerable number of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), including attack, surveillance, and reconnaissance drones. Saudi Arabia has actively pursued domestic drone manufacturing programs, such as the [Saqr](/Saqr_(drone)) and Samoom projects, and has engaged in technology transfer agreements and joint ventures with international partners, including Italy for [Selex Galileo Falco drones](/Selex_ES_Falco), China for [Wing Loong](/CAIG_Wing_Loong) drones, and Germany for [EMT Luna X-2000](/EMT_Luna_X-2000) drones. Recent agreements include a significant export contract with Turkey for [Baykar Bayraktar Akinci UCAVs](/Baykar_Bayraktar_Ak%C4%B1nc%C4%B1).

### Engagements and Conflicts

The RSAF has participated in numerous engagements throughout its history, reflecting the geopolitical landscape of the region. These include the [Hejaz–Nejd War](/Saudi_conquest_of_Hejaz), the [Al-Wadiah War](/Al-Wadiah_War), the [Action of 5 June 1984](/Action_of_5_June_1984), the [Gulf War](/Gulf_War), and more recently, operations in the [Syrian Civil War](/US_intervention_in_the_Syrian_civil_war), the [Houthi–Saudi Arabian conflict](/Houthi%E2%80%93Saudi_Arabian_conflict), the [War against ISIS](/War_against_the_Islamic_State), and the ongoing [Yemeni Civil War](/Saudi-led_intervention_in_the_Yemeni_civil_war).

### Command Structure

The ultimate authority rests with the [King](/King_of_Saudi_Arabia) as the [Commander-in-chief](/Commander-in-chief). Operational command is vested in the [Chairman of the General Staff](/Chairman_of_the_General_Staff), currently [Air Chief Marshal](/Air_chief_marshal) [Fayyadh Al-Ruwaili](/Fayyadh_Al_Ruwaili). The [Minister of Defense](/Ministry_of_Defense_(Saudi_Arabia)) is [Khalid bin Salman](/Khalid_bin_Salman_Al_Saud). The [Commander of Royal Air Force](/Commander_of_Royal_Air_Force_(Saudi_Arabia)) is [Lieutenant General](/Lieutenant_general) [Turki bin Bandar](/Turki_bin_Bandar_Al_Saud).

The RSAF has undergone a remarkable transformation, evolving from a nascent force into a sophisticated air power, capable of projecting force and defending the kingdom's interests in a complex and dynamic region. Its continued investment in advanced technology and strategic partnerships underscores its commitment to maintaining air superiority.